KW  - Federal Reserve
KW  - risk-taking channel
KW  - LSAP
KW  - portfolio substitution effect
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-2879
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.12781
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We empirically test early monetary theories in which reserve creation plays a crucial role in the transmission of quantitative easing (QE). Analyzing the unprecedented injection of reserves across several Federal Reserve QE programs, we demonstrate a causal effect of bank-level reserve accumulation on lending and risk-taking activity. To overcome the endogeneity of bank-level reserve increases to banks' other portfolio decisions, we employ instruments made available by a regulatory change that strongly influenced the distribution of reserves in the banking system. Consistent with the theory, we document that reserve creation leads to higher total loan growth and increased risk taking.
ER  - 

